## Vercel Web Analytics Implementation

Successfully installed and configured Vercel Web Analytics for this Next.js project.

### Changes Made

**Modified Files:**
- `app/layout.tsx` - Added Analytics component to the root layout
- `package.json` - Added @vercel/analytics dependency
- `package-lock.json` - Updated with new dependency tree

### Implementation Details

1. **Fetched Latest Documentation**: Retrieved the most up-to-date installation instructions from https://vercel.com/docs/analytics/quickstart

2. **Installed Package**: Added `@vercel/analytics` package using npm (the project's package manager based on the presence of package-lock.json)

3. **Configured Analytics**: 
   - Imported `Analytics` component from `@vercel/analytics/next`
   - Added the component to the root layout file at `app/layout.tsx`
   - Placed the `<Analytics />` component inside the `<body>` tag as recommended for Next.js App Router projects

### Framework Detection

This project uses:
- **Framework**: Next.js 16.2.9
- **Router**: App Router (confirmed by presence of app/layout.tsx)
- **Package Manager**: npm (confirmed by package-lock.json)

### Verification

✓ Build completed successfully with no errors
✓ TypeScript compilation passed
✓ No new linting errors introduced by the changes
✓ Analytics component properly integrated following official Vercel documentation

### Next Steps

To complete the setup:
1. Deploy the application to Vercel
2. Enable Analytics in the Vercel dashboard for your project
3. Verify functionality by checking the browser's Network tab for requests to `/_vercel/insights/*` and `/<unique-path>/view` after deployment

### Notes

- The implementation follows Next.js App Router patterns exactly as specified in the official Vercel documentation
- The Analytics component is placed at the end of the body tag to avoid blocking page rendering
- All existing code structure and formatting has been preserved
- Pre-existing linting warnings/errors in other files remain unchanged (not related to this implementation)
